sql:
SELECT run_id, average_choice_duration
FROM run_statistics
WHERE average_choice_duration > 3;

external_knowledge:
- "average choice duration" is calculated by averaging the choice durations of all trials within a run;
- "run" refers to a specific instance of an experiment or test involving multiple trials;
- "participant" refers to an individual who takes part in the experiment or test.

- A "run" in this context refers to a specific instance of an experiment;
- A "participant" is an individual who takes part in one or more trials of a run;
- The total number of runs a participant has been involved in is the sum of all unique runs they have participated in.

- 'RR' condition refers to a specific experimental condition that might involve repeated responses or rapid reactions;
- A positive feedback of 'Good job! You responded quickly.' indicates a high performance in terms of response time;
- The baseline average choice duration is calculated from a control run (run_id = 0);
- The mean values (mu1 and mu2) are statistical measures of the responses in the trial;
- The participant ID is filtered to include only male participants aged over 18.

